# Tommy Autopilot Protocol (chain-agnostic)

This project uses a Cursor `stop` hook to drive arbitrary multi-stage chains
defined in `.cursor/state/stages.json`. The currently active chain is
identified by `active_chain` and `chain_label` in that file (current chain:
**Tommy UX Parity** — align chat UX with ChatGPT/Cursor; reference plan at
`.cursor/plans/ux_parity_autopilot_5d06828e.plan.md`). When a chain finishes
the autopilot stops; loading a new chain is a one-shot operation outside any
agent turn (see Operator commands).

## Foreman + subagent execution model

Within an autopilot turn the parent agent (this conversation) is the
**foreman**, not the implementer. For each stage the foreman MUST:

1. Read the autopilot prompt that the stop hook injected (it carries the
   stage id, title, scope, and acceptance criteria) and re-read this rule.
2. Dispatch ONE implementer subagent via the Task tool with
   `subagent_type=generalPurpose`, `model=gpt-5.5-medium`. The prompt to the
   subagent must include: full stage scope verbatim, acceptance criteria,
   starting file paths, and a strict instruction to use native edit/terminal
   tools (no Markdown-only output). The subagent is told NOT to call
   `autopilot.sh complete`.
3. When the subagent returns, verify the work:
   - `python -m pytest -x -q` from `backend/` exits 0.
   - `python -m ruff check` from `backend/` exits 0.
   - Public API behavior is preserved unless the stage explicitly changes it.
   - New behavior has tests.
   - If schema changed, an Alembic migration is present and
     `alembic upgrade head` succeeds.
   - The stage-specific acceptance bullets are met.
4. If any gate fails, resume the same subagent (Task with `resume=<id>`) with
   a precise fix list. Allow up to **3 total attempts** per stage.
5. When all gates pass, run from the workspace root:
   ```bash
   ./.cursor/hooks/autopilot.sh complete <STAGE_ID>
   ```
   This is the ONLY signal the autopilot uses to advance. After the call,
   end your turn cleanly — the stop hook will inject the next stage's
   prompt automatically.
6. If after 3 attempts the gates still do not pass, run:
   ```bash
   ./.cursor/hooks/autopilot.sh block <STAGE_ID> "<one-line reason>"
   ```
   and stop the turn.

## Hard rules

- The foreman does NOT implement the stage directly. Always dispatch a
  subagent. Exception: trivial bootstrap / glue work outside any defined
  stage may be done directly.
- Decisions encoded in the chain's reference plan are final. Do not ask
  clarifying questions.
- Never call `autopilot.sh complete` for more than one stage per turn.
- Never call `autopilot.sh enable` / `disable` from inside a turn.
- Never edit `.cursor/state/stages.json` by hand — always go through
  `autopilot.sh` so the audit log in `.cursor/logs/autopilot.log` stays
  consistent.
- If the user explicitly says "stop autopilot" / "pause" / "halt", call
  `autopilot.sh disable` and end the turn.

## Operator commands (informational)

- `./.cursor/hooks/autopilot.sh status` — show the stage table.
- `./.cursor/hooks/autopilot.sh disable` / `enable` — pause / resume.
- `./.cursor/hooks/autopilot.sh unblock <STAGE_ID>` — clear a blocked stage.
- `./.cursor/hooks/autopilot.sh reset` — set every stage back to `pending`.
- `./.cursor/hooks/autopilot.sh set-chain <path/to/chain.json>` — load a
  fresh chain; replaces `stages.json` atomically and writes to the audit log.
